<dl id="s17017ae"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="us17" href="#s17017ae">Ithaca: </a><a href="../../ff/unbs/s17all.htm#s17017ae">sector 17(ae)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> 3% grade or pitch</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In the language of engineers the <mark><i>grade</i></mark> of an incline means the ratio of the height to the length of the incline, and is commonly expressed in the percentage form. Thus, a &ldquo;<mark>4 per cent grade</mark>&rdquo; means that in walking 100 ft. up the incline you rise 4 ft. Similarly, the <mark><i>pitch</i></mark> means the ratio of the height to the base. <small> Wentworth and Hill, <a name="TBOP" href="/udra/udex.htm#tbop"><cite title="source">A Text-Book of Physics</cite></a> (1904), 35</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
